In Lab 3 you will be asked to produce graphics using ggplot2, a nice graphics package in R. This prelab is meant to give you some practice ahead of time, and we focus on two types of graphics: histograms and scatter plots.

I encourage you to try to replicate all the graphs in this prelab in your own RStudio session.

In order to produce graphics with ggplot2, you need to load it into your RStudio session. The ggplot2 package is part of the tidyverse package, so begin your session by loading the tidyverse. Recall, do do this, run the line

library(tidyverse)

With the tidyverse loaded, you are ready to use the ggplot functions for generating graphs.

All the plots in this prelab use the Old Faithful data set that comes built-in to the RStudio program.

With the code below, you can load the data into your session with the working name of (short for old faithful). The code also displays the first five rows of the data frame, to help familiarize yourself with the data set. The data set records information about \(n = 272\) eruptions of the Old Faithful geyser. The eruptions variable indicates how long the eruption lasted (in minutes), and the waiting variable indicates how long the wait was between eruptions (in minutes).

of <- faithful
head(of,5)
##   eruptions waiting
## 1     3.600      79
## 2     1.800      54
## 3     3.333      74
## 4     2.283      62
## 5     4.533      85

Code for plots with the ggplot package will have this general look:

ggplot(data=..., aes(x=...,y=...,...)) + 
  geom_'type of plot you want'(options) + 
  bells + 
  whistles + 
  other options

Two remarks before showing many examples.

  1. We need those + signs! We need to add a + sign to the end of a line if we want to add another feature to the plot.
  2. We specify our variables from the data set inside the aes() command to input our variables, and aes is short for aesthetic.

Histograms with ggplot

Use the geom_histogrm() plot type command, and specify x inside aes().

Basic Histogram

ggplot(data = of, aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2)

Specifying the bins for a histogram is good practice. You can either specify the bin widths as weve done here with the option binwidth=2, or we can specify the total number of bins by entering the option bins = 20, for instance.

Add color and axis labels

ggplot(data = of,aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2,col="blue",fill="yellow") + 
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Histogram of Old Faithful Wait Times")

The col option colors the boundary of each bar, the fill option colors the interior of each bar. If we want to change the y-axis label, we use the code ylab("enter new label here inside quotes").

Change the theme

If youre not a fan of the gray plot background, you can change the theme. Here are two other options:

ggplot(data = of,aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2, col="blue", fill="yellow") + 
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Histogram of Old Faithful Wait Times") + 
  theme_classic()

ggplot(data = of,aes(x=eruptions)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, col="white", fill="dodgerblue") + 
  xlab("Eruption duration (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Histogram of Old Faithful Eruption Durations") + 
  theme_bw()

Notice in this last plot I changed from binwidths to specifying the number of bins. By the way, I really like the color dodgerblue even though Im not a huge Dodgers fan.

Bonus Round - Density Plot

Instead of a histogram of counts, we can produce a histogram of frequencies by adding the option aes(y = ..density..) as below. This will produce a histogram which records the proportion of the values falling in each bin, not the total counts.

ggplot(of, aes(x=eruptions)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), bins=20, col="white", fill="dodgerblue",alpha = 0.4)

We remark that the alpha option above refers to the opacity of the fill color. Values of alpha range from 0 to 1, with lower values corresponding to more transparent colors. So in this plot the dodgerblue color has been made more transparent. If we had set alpha = 1, the color would look as it did in the previous histogram.

ggplot(of, aes(x=eruptions)) + 
  geom_density() + 
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(eruptions)),
            color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1)

The geom_density() function gives an idealized density plot rather than a histogram.

The geom_vline() option above was thrown in just for fun. It places a vertical line in the graph, for which weve specified these options: the color is blue, it is dashed, and it hits the x-axis at the mean value of the eruptions. This distribution is clearly bimodal!!

Scatter Plots with ggplot

Use the geom_point() plot type command, and specify x and y inside aes().

Basic scatter plot

ggplot(data = of,aes(x=waiting,y=eruptions)) +
  geom_point()

Add color and axis labels

ggplot(data = of,aes(x=waiting,y=eruptions)) +
  geom_point(col="seagreen")+
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ylab("eruption duration (min)") +
  ggtitle("Old Faithful") + 
  theme_bw()

Seagreen! I like it!

R has lots (657) of built-in color names. You can see the names in RStudio if you run colors().

Add color by category

Lets add a categorical variable called arrival that takes the value early if the wait time was less than 70 minutes and late if the wait time is 70 minutes or more (and then check the first 10 entries to see if the code seems to be working :))

of$arrival = ifelse(of$waiting<70,"early","late")
head(of,10)
##    eruptions waiting arrival
## 1      3.600      79    late
## 2      1.800      54   early
## 3      3.333      74    late
## 4      2.283      62   early
## 5      4.533      85    late
## 6      2.883      55   early
## 7      4.700      88    late
## 8      3.600      85    late
## 9      1.950      51   early
## 10     4.350      85    late

We can color points in a scatter plot according to a categorical variable by specifying col = this variable within the aes() command.

ggplot(data = of,aes(x=waiting,y=eruptions,col=arrival)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ylab("eruption duration (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Old Faithful") + 
  theme_bw()

Bonus Round - Fit the line

The code geom_smooth(method='lm', formula=y~x) adds the least squares regression line to the scatter plot.

ggplot(data = of,aes(x=waiting, y = eruptions)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', formula=y~x) +
  theme_bw()

The gray bar of varying thickness surrounding the least squares regression line is called a confidence band, something we wont consider here. To remove it from a plot, add the se = FALSE option in your geom_smooth() line. While were at it, lets spruce up the look of it all:

ggplot(data = of,aes(x=waiting, y = eruptions)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method='lm',, formula=y~x, col="blue",size=.8,se=FALSE) +
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ylab("eruption duration (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Old Faithful data with least squares regression line") + 
  theme_bw()
